<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Wednesday.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-wei=
ght: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-ser=
if; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom=
: 0;">GME</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is George Sherman one of the gre=
atest public-company chief executive officers in American history? He becam=
e CEO of GameStop Corp. on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYX=
RhLzEzMjYzODAvMDAwMTMyNjM4MDE5MDAwMDMwL2V4OTkxcHJlc3NyZWxlYXNlY2VvYXBwb2luL=
mh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7d7b31bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">April 15, 2019</a>. The stock closed at $8=
.94 per share that day. On April 19, 2021 =E2=80=94=C2=A0almost exactly two=
 years later =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kY=
XRhLzEzMjYzODAvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMTIwMzA0L2QzMDc1OTlkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB190e449d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">GameStop announced</a> that he will be stepping down by July.=
 The stock closed at $164.37 that day. That=E2=80=99s a 1,739% return over =
his two-year term, or about 325% annualized. (The S&amp;P 500 index was up =
43%, or about 20% a year, over those two years.) GameStop=E2=80=99s market =
capitalization went from about $900 million to about $11.5 billion; Sherman=
 added about $10.5 billion of shareholder value in two years.[1]=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How much should he get paid, for doing this ama=
zing work for shareholders? A billion dollars? Two billion? If GameStop=E2=
=80=99s shareholders had only gotten the S&amp;P 500 return over the last f=
ew years, they=E2=80=99d have missed out on more than $10 billion in value;=
 I suppose you could make a case that they should be willing to pay Sherman=
 up to $10 billion for his magic touch.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">But GameStop shareholders <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9nYW1lc3Rv=
cHMtY2VvLWlzLWdldHRpbmctbWlsbGlvbnMtb24taGlzLXdheS1vdXQtaGVzLW5vdC10aGUtb25=
seS1vbmUtMTE2MTkzNTY4MjM_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBa2a6394a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">got a=C2=A0bargain</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It i=
s a lucrative time to be leaving GameStop Corp.=E2=80=99s=C2=A0C-suite as t=
he run-up in the videogame retailer=E2=80=99s share price has enabled four =
executives to depart with vested stock now valued at roughly $290 million.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Separation agreements between GameStop and =
the four executives, including Chief Executive Officer George Sherman, have=
 provisions that let stock awarded during their tenure to vest when they le=
ave. While such a handling of leadership transitions isn=E2=80=99t atypical=
, it does potentially allow the executives to sell their shares near GameSt=
op=E2=80=99s historically high levels. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
GameStop has said that Mr. Sherman will step down by July 31 and that it is=
 searching for his replacement. His exit agreement calls for the accelerate=
d vesting of more than 1.1 million GameStop shares, according to filings, v=
alued at roughly $169 million as of Friday=E2=80=99s close.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Sherman=E2=80=99s severance pay could have been higher=
. According to his separation agreement and GameStop=E2=80=99s recent proxy=
 filing, the CEO agreed to give up at least $5 million in cash, stock value=
d at roughly $47 million as of Friday, and additional equity awards. No rea=
son was given for the changes, and Mr. Sherman declined to comment.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They make it sound like a bad thing!<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Obviously I am kidding a little.=C2=A0I don=
=E2=80=99t know what to tell you. Ordinarily the way executive compensation=
 works is, like:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You hire a CEO ho=
ping that he will do good things to make the company better.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shorthand way of measuring that is the stock=
 price: The stock price discounts all the future cash flows of the company,=
 so the more long-term value that the CEO adds to the company, the higher t=
he stock price will be.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Thus you m=
ight tie compensation explicitly to the stock price (give the CEO a bigger =
bonus if the stock price goes up a lot, etc.), or you might just pay the CE=
O largely in the form of stock and stock options, so that the higher the st=
ock price goes the more his compensation will be worth.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the stock price goes up=C2=A0<em>three hundred twe=
nty-five percent a year=C2=A0</em>during the CEO=E2=80=99s tenure, then tha=
t is very very very very very good, he has added an unheard-of amount of lo=
ng-term value to the company, and you should be absolutely thrilled to pay =
him a=C2=A0ton of money.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ordinarily t=
here are quibbles. The stock price is not a perfect measure of long-term va=
lue: Investors can arguably take a short-term perspective, stock prices can=
 arguably=C2=A0be juiced through financial engineering, stock prices arguab=
ly do not reflect the value that the company provides to (or takes away fro=
m) non-shareholder stakeholders, etc. Nobody really says =E2=80=9CCEOs shou=
ld be compensated purely based on stock price appreciation.=E2=80=9D Still =
the=C2=A0model above has an obvious appeal, and it is the basic starting po=
int for most executive compensation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">GameSt=
op=E2=80=99s stock is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0look, I truly know nothing, but I thin=
k it is reasonably fair to say that GameStop=E2=80=99s stock is not up 1,73=
9% over two years because=C2=A0George Sherman revolutionized its business. =
GameStop had a net loss of $673 million in the fiscal year just before Sher=
man took over; it had a net loss of $215 million in the fiscal year just be=
fore he left. An improvement! But not great. GameStop is up 1,739% because:=
</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px=
 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In late 2020, Ryan Cohen, a found=
er of Chewy.com with a history of success in internet sales, bought a lot o=
f stock and became an activist pushing for a new digital strategy. Cohen su=
cceeded in winning over the board: He=E2=80=99s on the board and=C2=A0<a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9nYW1lc3RvcC10by1uYW1lLWNoZXd5LWNvLWZvdW5kZX=
Itcnlhbi1jb2hlbi1hcy1jaGFpcm1hbi0xMTYxNzg4Mjg2Ng/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8=
6c59196" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">w=
ill become=C2=A0its chairman</a>, work is underway on the digital transform=
ation, Cohen-picked executives with good digital track records are joining =
GameStop in senior positions, etc.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>Retail investors on Reddit like the stock.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910=
.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDE=
tMjUvdGhlLWdhbWUtbmV2ZXItc3RvcHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB315ef5d3" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Short squeeze</a=
>.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Rocket rocket rocket diamond ha=
nds.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When I first wrote about George =
Sherman,=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2365=
6910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjE=
tMDEtMjcvcmVkZGl0LWRyaXZlbi1zdXJnZS1wdXRzLWdhbWVzdG9wLWFuZC1yeWFuLWNvaGVuLW=
luLWEtd2VpcmQtc3BvdA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5adea445" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I said</a>:=C2=A0</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One possible conclusion here is that the w=
orld in which GameStop is a fun gambling token and up a zillion percent rea=
lly is cut off from the world in which GameStop is a company with a CEO and=
 a board and 5,000 struggling stores in malls and a big activist investor w=
ith plans to turn its business around. They can see each other, but they ca=
n never interact. =E2=80=9CHuh, lotta crazy news about something called =E2=
=80=98GameStop,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D George Sherman or Ryan Cohen might think;=
 =E2=80=9Cit would be weird if they were talking about us.=E2=80=9D But the=
y=E2=80=99re not.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could ar=
gue that I was wrong about Cohen, and that the stock-price surge really was=
 due to rational optimism about his plans. Sherman, not so much. He seems t=
o have been largely a bystander as his company became a meme. And now he ge=
ts paid. =E2=80=9CIt does potentially allow the executives to sell their sh=
ares near GameStop=E2=80=99s historically high levels.=E2=80=9D Ordinarily =
that=E2=80=99s the whole point of executive compensation! The whole point i=
s to pay executives more when the stock price goes up, so that they will ha=
ve incentives to do things that make the stock price go up. But in 2021, wi=
th GameStop, the stock price became disconnected from the business. But not=
 from the executive compensation.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile=
 who=E2=80=99s gonna be the new CEO? And how will that person get paid? Do =
you give the new CEO stock options struck at like $300? If the stock falls =
back to, say, $90 =E2=80=94=C2=A0up 400% from the start of 2021! =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0that will be a disaster for the new CEO. The market seems to think th=
at GameStop is an $11 billion company. Does its board think that? (The comp=
any is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910.28=
9653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMD=
UvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1zLWFyY2hlZ29zLXN3YXAtYWZ0ZXJtYXRoLWlzLWF3a3dhcmQtZm9yLWJhb=
mtz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBcb119d85" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> selling stock</a> at these levels.) Does the =
new CEO? Never mind what Sherman did or did not do, as CEO; just look at=C2=
=A0how much the stock price increased during his tenure. How do you follow =
that act?</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black=
&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5p=
x; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">SPAC SPAC SPAC</h2><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The way an initial public offering works is that a bank helps =
a company go public by selling stock to new investors, and in exchange the =
bank takes a fee of roughly 1% to 7% of the amount the company raises. Lots=
 of people think these fees =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly the 7% fees that ar=
e standard in smaller IPOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0are too high.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The way a special purpose acquisition company works is that a =
sponsor helps a company go public by selling stock to new investors, and in=
 return the sponsor takes stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cpromote=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94 equal to 20% of the amount the company sells.[2] A bank helps too=
, and charges a separate 5.5% fee.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An im=
portant point about SPACs is that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMjcvc3BhY3MtYXJlbi10LWNoZWFwZXItdGhhbi1pcG9zLXlldA=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB72051b13" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> 20% is more than 7%</a>? I mean! These numbers a=
re not apples-to-apples. The 20% is paid in stock, not cash; usually the sp=
onsor will be required to hold onto the stock for a while. (Whereas IPO ban=
ks just get a check and move on.) Often the sponsors, or funds that they ru=
n, will also invest their own (funds=E2=80=99) money in the SPAC, alongside=
 the free stock that they get. (Whereas IPO banks are generally just servic=
e providers, not co-investors.) And that free stock isn=E2=80=99t exactly f=
ree; the SPAC sponsors will have to put up a bit of money to cover startup =
expenses, though they get the stock at a huge discount. (Whereas IPO banks =
pay for fewer expenses, though not none; someone=E2=80=99s gotta pay for sn=
acks at the roadshow.) Also the SPAC deal will often have a PIPE deal (priv=
ate investment in public equity) alongside it, raising more money that is n=
ot subject to=C2=A0the sponsor promote.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sti=
ll 20% (or 25.5%) really is more than 7%, never mind the 1% to 3% fees that=
 are more common in larger IPOs. And so tons of celebrities became vaguely =
affiliated with SPACs, because SPACS are incredibly lucrative and <a href=
