r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">here is a memo from Akin Gump Strauss Hauer &amp; Feld</a>=C2=A0about =
how plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyers have started suing SPACs for allegedly poor=
 disclosures in their de-SPAC mergers:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">The complaints focus on the SPAC=E2=80=99s disclosures regarding a =
proposed de-SPAC business combination. Specifically, the complaints general=
ly allege inadequate disclosures, targeting certain categories of informati=
on that are allegedly materially misleading or incomplete in the publicly f=
iled initial SPAC merger announcement. The SEC=E2=80=99s December 2020 SPAC=
 disclosure guidance covers some of these categories of allegedly misstated=
 or omitted information. For example, the complaints track the SEC=E2=80=99=
s disclosure guidance regarding the continued relationship, if any, the SPA=
C=E2=80=99s directors or officers may have with the combined company, poten=
tially giving rise to conflicts of interest with the interests of public sh=
areholders.=C2=A0The complaints also frequently allege inadequate disclosur=
es relating to the SPAC=E2=80=99s financial advisor=E2=80=99s compensation,=
 including whether any portion is contingent upon consummation of the de-SP=
AC transaction, and potential conflicts of interest arising from the financ=
ial advisor=E2=80=99s past services for any parties to the transaction.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When=C2=A0a SPAC finds a company =
to take public, it signs a merger agreement and publishes a proxy statement=
 so its public shareholders can vote on the deal. The U.S. Securities and E=
xchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluL2Rpc2Nsb3N1cmUtc3BlY2=
lhbC1wdXJwb3NlLWFjcXVpc2l0aW9uLWNvbXBhbmllcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4054d=
d1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">has s=
colded SPACs</a> about the sorts of things they should disclose in those pr=
oxies, conflicts of interest and financial incentives and continuing relati=
onships that the sponsors might have. If the proxy doesn=E2=80=99t fully di=
sclose these things, in theory, the shareholder vote will not be fully info=
rmed; lawyers will sue to hold up the shareholder vote until the proxy is f=
ixed. The idea is that the SPAC will settle the case by (1) agreeing to rev=
ise the proxy to include more disclosure and (2) pay the plaintiffs=E2=80=
=99 lawyers a=C2=A0fee. This was a common move in mergers-and-acquisitions =
transactions =E2=80=94=C2=A0it was referred to as the =E2=80=9CM&amp;A tax,=
=E2=80=9D because every deal had to pay off some plaintiffs=E2=80=99 lawyer=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0until <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucGF1bHdlaXNzLmNvbS9wcmFjdGljZXMvdHJhbn=
NhY3Rpb25hbC9tZXJnZXJzLWFjcXVpc2l0aW9ucy9wdWJsaWNhdGlvbnMvZGVsYXdhcmUtY291c=
nQtb2YtY2hhbmNlcnktcmVqZWN0cy1hbm90aGVyLWRpc2Nsb3N1cmUtb25seS1zZXR0bGVtZW50=
P2lkPTIxNDAz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB604770e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Delaware courts got sick of it</a=
>=C2=A0and stopped approving these settlements. But these cases are filed i=
n New York, and=C2=A0 against SPACs, so perhaps now there will be a SPAC ta=
x.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess the point here is that this is s=
ort of trivial, garden-variety stuff? The real money in suing SPACs is sure=
ly:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 1=
6px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A SPAC takes a company=C2=A0pu=
blic at a high price with optimistic projections.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">The projections don=E2=80=99t work out.</li>=09<li style=3D=
"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company goes to zero.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Sue!</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you sue to hold=
 up a shareholder vote, the best you=E2=80=99re going to do is get a six-fi=
gure-ish fee when the SPAC settles by revising its proxy. If you wait to=C2=
=A0sue until investors have lost a billion dollars, you can sue for a billi=
on dollars! And take like 20% of it for lawyers=E2=80=99 fees! There is a t=
heory that SPACs can say whatever they like in their projections without ge=
tting sued, but there=E2=80=99s also a theory =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTIvbWF5YmUtc3BhY3MtYXJ=
lLXJlYWxseS1pcG9z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC638ae35b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">kind of endorsed by the SEC?</a>=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they can=E2=80=99t, and if you are an adventurous plai=
ntiffs=E2=80=99 lawyer surely you can argue that theory.[5] =E2=80=9CThe Be=
ginning Wave of SPAC Litigation,=E2=80=9D Akin Gump calls it, but I think e=
ven that is premature; the real lawsuits will go after the SPACs that don=
=E2=80=99t work out.</p>
