ctc2NoZW1lLXN0ZWFsaW5nLW92ZXItMzAtbWlsbGlvbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB590dd=
a84" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">three=
 guys from Brooklyn</a> who allegedly=C2=A0noticed that banks in eastern Eu=
rope=C2=A0were not as secure as banks in Brooklyn, and so decided to rob th=
em. Here is=C2=A0how they allegedly robbed them:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">As set forth in the indictment and court filings, between=
 March 2015 and October 2019, the defendants and their co-conspirators alle=
gedly stole over $30 million in cash and other valuables from safe deposit =
boxes at banks in multiple foreign countries, including the Ukraine, Russia=
, North Macedonia, Moldova, Latvia, Uzbekistan and Azerbaijan.=C2=A0 The co=
-conspirators targeted foreign banks that appeared to lack security feature=
s, including video surveillance cameras in certain areas.=C2=A0 After a ban=
k was selected, they rented safe deposit boxes at the location by posing as=
 customers.=C2=A0 The co-conspirators entered the safe deposit box rooms of=
 the targeted banks and used sophisticated camera equipment, including bore=
scopes that are typically used in medical procedures, to photograph the ins=
ides of locks of safe deposit boxes belonging to other individuals.=C2=A0 A=
nother co-conspirator used these photographs to create duplicate keys, and =
then other co-conspirators used the duplicate keys to open the victim safe =
deposit boxes in order to steal the contents, including currency, gold bars=
, jewelry and other property.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">I=E2=80=99m sorry but that=E2=80=99s cool. Photographing the inside o=
f locks of safe deposit boxes?=C2=A0That is just fun bank heisting. =E2=80=
=9CThe crimes we allege in this indictment read like something straight out=
 of Hollywood fiction,=E2=80=9D says an FBI agent in the press release, and=
 he is right. Good story!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Weird that they w=
ere arrested? To be clear, this is not a case of police in =E2=80=9CUkraine=
, Russia, North Macedonia, Moldova, Latvia, Uzbekistan and Azerbaijan=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0noticing the crimes, identifying the perpetrators, tracking them t=
o Brooklyn and asking U.S. authorities to arrest and extradite them. This i=
s the U.S. Attorney for the Eastern District of New York arresting them on =
his own initiative, not to ship them off to Ukraine etc. to be prosecuted f=
or bank robbery, but to prosecute them in Brooklyn <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS=
5nb3YvdXNhby1lZG55L3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvZmlsZS8xMzg4Mjg2L2Rvd25sb2Fk/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBaeb11b45" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">for =E2=80=A6=C2=A0money =E2=80=A6=C2=A0laundering</a>?</p=
><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The defendants and their co-consp=
irators agreed to use the United States financial system in furtherance of =
these crimes. For example, a co-conspirator =E2=80=A6=C2=A0used a credit ca=
rd issued in the United States =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to make multiple purchases to=
 promote the bank thefts, including, among other things (i) to purchase air=
line tickets to fly from, among other places, the Eastern District of New Y=
ork to the locations of the thefts; and (ii) to rent hotel rooms for COOPER=
 and the defendant GARRI SMITH, among others. The defendant ALEX LEVIN used=
 bank accounts in the United States, including accounts located in the East=
ern District=C2=A0of New York, among other things, to purchase sophisticate=
d camera equipment used in the thefts, some of which was shipped to LEVIN=
=E2=80=99s residence in the Eastern District of New York, and to launder th=
e proceeds of those crimes.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Th=
e U.S. financial system is amazing. If you use a U.S. credit card to buy a =
plane ticket to a foreign country, and then you do a crime in that country,=
 that=E2=80=99s also a crime in the U.S. (It violates the <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23656910.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWt=
pcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvVHJhdmVsX0FjdA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3da0af84" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Travel Act</a>=
.) And if you rob a bank abroad,=C2=A0deposit the proceeds of the heist int=
o a U.S. checking account, and use the money to pay your rent or whatever, =
that=E2=80=99s a big U.S. crime; that=E2=80=99s (allegedly) =E2=80=9Cmoney =
laundering.=E2=80=9D Everything is money laundering.=C2=A0</p><h2 style=3D"=
font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, =
sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margi=
n-bottom: 0;">Dual-class IPOs</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic st=
ory I like to tell about dual-class IPOs goes like this. Once upon a time c=
ompanies needed money; when they went public, it was to tap a large pool of=
 capital that they needed to grow their business. Money was hard to get, so=
 the companies were solicitous of public investors. There was a norm that, =
if you invested money in a risky, newly public company, you got some say in=
 how the company was run. Not=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>much say, but just regu=
lar shareholder rights. You got voting stock, at least, so you could vote f=
or directors and maybe kick them out if they did a bad job.</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">But in modern markets companies have a much easier time of=
 raising money. There is a ton of money out there, due to general liquidity=
 conditions,=C2=A0the globalization of the capital markets, technological i=
nnovations that have made capital raising easier, etc. Meanwhile globalized=
 product markets are increasingly winner-take-all; if you have a good idea =
it will make a lot of money for your investors. The result is that investor=
s need companies more than companies need investors: Money is plentiful but=
 good investments are scarce. So the balance of power has shifted: Investor=
s are not valuable partners whose desires must be taken seriously; they=E2=
=80=99re just fungible sources of cash, and if they annoy a company it can =
just go elsewhere. The balance of power has shifted so that entrepreneurs a=
re in control and shareholders have to do whatever they say.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">And one thing that entrepreneurs really want, besides mon=
ey, is perpetual control of their companies. They identify with their compa=
nies; they built them; they feel like they own them. They want to raise cas=
h from public shareholders without giving up control to those shareholders.=
 And now they don=E2=80=99t have to.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
Here are a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2365691=
0.289653/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2=
